node.text:
President Biden and numerous New York leaders called on Gov. Andrew Cuomo to resign Tuesday following the release of a damning state attorney general’s report that found he sexually harassed multiple women under his employ. 

From the governors of multiple states to Cuomo’s own allies in New York, Democrats appear ready to close the book on a three-term governor once thought to be a presidential contender. Read more at the link in bio.

https://politi.co/3rQEyAa

node.text:
White House press secretary Jen Psaki forcefully defended the Biden administration’s growing offensive on vaccine-related misinformation spreading on Facebook and other social media platforms.

“For how long has the administration been spying on people’s Facebook profiles looking for vaccine misinformation?” Fox News’ Peter Doocy asked, referencing Psaki’s comments a day prior that roughly a dozen people on Facebook were responsible for the bulk of vaccine misinformation on the social network.

Psaki called the characterization “a loaded and inaccurate question.” She said that the concerning posts that the White House flagged to platforms like Facebook is similar to the outreach officials have with news outlets when they take issue with particular coverage. Read more at the link in bio.

node.text:
Defense Secretary Lloyd Austin will seek to make the Covid-19 vaccine mandatory for all of its 1.4 million service members by mid-September, a date that could be accelerated if needed.

The move follows Biden's directive that the Pentagon examine how and when it could mandate the shot for the military. The president last month mandated all federal workers either get the vaccine or submit to frequent testing and travel restrictions. 

Austin’s memo today reflects similar decisions taken by governments and private companies globally, as the world again struggles with the spread of the highly contagious Delta variant that has sent new U.S. cases, hospitalizations and deaths surge to levels not seen since the winter months. Over 30 percent of active-duty troops have not been vaccinated. Read more at the link in bio.

📸 Getty 

https://politi.co/3fMQdLu

node.text:
Almost exactly a year ago, as aides to former President Donald Trump debated whether to label the Chinese government’s abuse of Uyghur Muslims a “genocide,” Joe Biden’s presidential campaign beat them to the punch. A campaign spokesperson said Biden believed the Uyghurs were genocide victims and that Trump needed to “take action” to stop the group’s suffering. 

This raised a question: If Biden thought the Uyghurs were genocide victims, did he believe the same thing about Myanmar’s Rohingya Muslims, who’d been facing mass slaughter, mass detention and mass displacement? Such a designation by the U.S. government would bolster the Rohingya’s international legal cases against Myanmar’s rulers while sending a warning to other would-be genocidaires, advocates say.

There’s no sign, however, that the Biden team is willing to make the call. Read more at the link in bio.

📸 AP

https://politi.co/37x6m2Z

node.text:
The long-feared era of disastrous climate change has arrived.
 
In a monumental report, the planet’s top scientists said they have definitively linked greenhouse gas emissions to disasters driven by a warmer climate that have touched every corner of the globe this year:
➡️ wildfires and heat waves across the world (Greece is pictured above) 
➡️ extreme rainfall in Germany and China
➡️ brutal droughts in the western U.S.
➡️ a record cyclone in the Philippines (swipe to the end 👈)
 
Even grimmer: There’s no scenario in which we avoid surpassing the 1.5 degrees Celsius threshold that the U.S., EU and other countries have set as a target.
 
The report comes as world leaders grapple with policies to wring carbon dioxide and methane emissions from their economies — and as the Senate moves forward on an infrastructure plan that takes only modest steps toward addressing climate change.
 
Research shows nations must start playing defense to withstand the weather disasters that will only grow worse unless emissions from fossil fuels are eliminated. Link in bio for more.

node.text:
Congress is preparing to order the biggest U.S. investment in history for fighting climate change. Scientists say it won’t be nearly enough.

A warning is set to arrive Monday from the United Nation's premier climate science panel, whose findings come as the Dixie Fire burning in Northern California is now the largest single wildfire in recorded state history. 

Lawmakers pushing for an aggressive climate offensive hope the report will finally jolt some action out of Washington. Democrats have included some climate measures in the Senate’s $550 billion infrastructure compromise bill, but they're calling for more sweeping efforts in the expected $3.5 trillion reconciliation package.

Previous assessments have eliminated the uncertainties politicians clung to when rejecting policies that threatened to disrupted the oil, gas and coal industries. Now, the scientists' focus is on how fast — not if — the disastrous changes to the Earth’s climate will occur, how people will adapt to them and how governments can ease the worst impacts. Link in bio for more.

📷: AP

node.text:
People in states hardest hit by the Delta variant are seeking out Covid-19 vaccines, but weary public health officials worry the renewed interest will fizzle.

The number of Americans receiving a first vaccine dose each week has nearly doubled over the last month. On July 30, Alabama vaccinated more than 16,000 people — the first time it had cleared that threshold since May. Louisiana, which is experiencing the worst Covid-19 outbreak in the country, has seen the number of doses administered each day quadruple over the last three weeks.

State and local officials in these areas say that fears about the spread of the highly contagious Delta variant, and the risk of death, are finally driving more people to seek out shots — succeeding where months of concerted appeals from pastors, pop stars and politicians have failed.

But whether the recent spike in demand will meaningfully boost vaccination rates, which are still below 50 percent in more than a dozen states, remains to be seen. 

Read more at the link in bio.

Over the past 15 years, an oil rush of mammoth proportions has planted more than 5,000 wells deep beneath the prairie of McKenzie County, North Dakota, making it the top oil-producing county in the U.S. Swipe 👈 to see photos.

But installing an industry atop an agricultural zone has led to environmental issues, including an elaborate system of saltwater tanks holding billions of gallons of contaminated water. brine, hydrocarbons, radioactive materials and more produced by oil fracking. 

More than 50 saltwater spills happen each year in McKenzie, when tanker trucks crash, pipelines leak or well pads or disposal sites catch fire or otherwise malfunction. Many spills are contained on well pads and at disposal sites. But others drain into fields, farmyards, waterways and roadways.

Increasingly, local landowners in McKenzie County — which voted more than 80 percent in favor of Donald Trump in 2020 — are pushing state leaders for more regulation and more accountability from the oil companies in their county. Read more at the link in bio.

📸 Dan Koeck for Politico Magazine

Florida Governor Ron DeSantis had a message for President Biden: “If you are trying to lock people down, I am standing in your way and I’m standing for the people of Florida." 

Biden's response: "Governor who?"

DeSantis' comments come after Biden on Wednesday called on Republican governors to “get out of the way” of vaccine rules aimed at containing the Covid-19 Delta variant.

“If you’re not going to help, at least get out of the way of people trying to do the right thing," Biden said.

Desantis' response came that same evening. "Joe Biden suggests that if you don't do lockdown policies then you should quote 'get out the way,'" the governor said. "But let me tell you this, if you're coming after the rights of parents in Florida, I'm standing in your way. I'm not gonna let you get away with it."

When asked about DeSantis’ comments, the president gave his succinct response.

node.text:
Richard Trumka, president of the powerful AFL-CIO labor organization, has died unexpectedly, sources say.

Trumka, 72, had served as president of the federation, which represents more than 12.5 million workers, for more than a decade and has been a close ally of the Biden White House.

“It’s just horrible news,” Senate Majority Leader Chuck Schumer said on the Senate floor. “He had in his veins, in every atom of his body, the heart, the thoughts, the needs of the working people of America. He was them. Rich Trumka was the working people of America.”

A third-generation coal miner, Trumka spent his career in the labor movement, serving as president of the United Mine Workers of America and as a member of the AFL-CIO’s executive counsel, as well as on various federation committees before being elected AFL-CIO president in 2009. Link in bio for more.

📷 AP

Florida school districts are moving to resist Gov. Ron DeSantis’ order barring schools from implementing mask requirements for kids. 

Late Tuesday night, school board members in Alachua County in north Florida voted to require all students to wear masks during the first two weeks of school. And Wednesday morning, Leon County announced it’s seeking a mandatory mask rule for students in pre-kindergarten through eighth grade. 

Both are direct rejections of DeSantis’ executive order prohibiting schools from enacting mask requirements for students.

The recent moves highlight how school districts across Florida are coping with the surge in coronavirus cases while grappling with DeSantis’ rejection of Covid mandates. District leaders are left to choose: Eliminate mask mandates or face the loss of state funding. Link in bio for more.

node.text:
The FDA is expected to approve Pfizer’s coronavirus vaccine by early September, amid a resurgence of cases that has heightened pressure on the administration to get more Americans vaccinated.

While the agency had long eyed the fall for granting full licensure, officials have recently accelerated their work, and now hope to finalize approval in a matter of weeks, according to sources.

Regulators authorized Pfizer’s two-dose vaccine for emergency use last December, followed quickly by Moderna. But full approval is a higher bar that health officials hope will nudge hesitant Americans towards getting vaccinated.
